**Elasticsearch version** (`bin/elasticsearch --version`): 7.0.0-SNAPSHOT

**Description of the problem including expected versus actual behavior**:
When calling `_cat/indices` with no index list, indices for which the user does not have privileges simply omit the docs count and storage size information.  However, calling the same API _with_ an index for which the user does not have privileges (`_cat/indices/index_you_cant_see_info_for`) returns a 403 error:
```
{
  "error": {
    "root_cause": [
      {
        "type": "security_exception",
        "reason": "action [indices:monitor/stats] is unauthorized for user [billy]"
      }
    ],
    "type": "security_exception",
    "reason": "action [indices:monitor/stats] is unauthorized for user [billy]"
  },
  "status": 403
}
```

I think the API should behave the same in either case, just return the data without storage size and docs count.

Elasticsearch offers support for a type of fields known as `aliases`: https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/6.x/alias.html

ES-SQL relies on [`_field_caps` ](https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/search-field-caps.html) to build the list of fields for an index and, at the moment, this API doesn't have support for "alias" fields in the sense of differentiating between an alias field and a normal field. In general field aliases are supported in ES-SQL (and are regarded in the same way `_field_caps` regards them - normal fields), but there are some scenarios where these don't work.

For the following mapping:

```
{
  "mappings": {
    "doc": {
      "properties": {
        "foo_alias": {
          "type": "alias",
          "path": "parent.foo"
        },
        "parent": {
          "properties": {
            "foo": {
              "type": "keyword",
              "ignore_above": 1024
            }
          }
        },
        "nested.foo_alias": {
          "type": "alias",
          "path": "parent.foo"
        },
        "nested": {
          "properties": {
            "foo_alias": {
              "type": "alias",
              "path": "parent.foo"
            }
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Both `nested.foo_alias` and `nested`->`foo_alias` alias fields will fail in ES-SQL. The reason is that when index resolution happens, when SQL tries to add `foo_alias` to the `nested` field, this doesn't exist and an exception will be thrown 

```
Server error [Server encountered an error [Cannot find field nested; this is likely a bug]. [SqlIllegalArgumentException[Cannot find field nested; this is likely a bug]
        at org.elasticsearch.xpack.sql.analysis.index.IndexResolver.createField(IndexResolver.java:355)
        at org.elasticsearch.xpack.sql.analysis.index.IndexResolver.mergedMapping(IndexResolver.java:329)
        at org.elasticsearch.xpack.sql.analysis.index.IndexResolver.lambda$resolveAsMergedMapping$3(IndexResolver.java:246)
```

`_field_caps` will report `nested.foo_alias` field but it won't report any `nested` field:

```
        "nested.foo_alias": {
            "keyword": {
                "type": "keyword",
                "searchable": true,
                "aggregatable": true
            }
        }
```

but SQL is expecting a `nested` separate field report in `_field_caps` as well.

Related issue https://github.com/elastic/elasticsearch/issues/37141.
